# android compose

- Prefer unidirectional data flow with ViewModel-owned UI state.
- Use Kotlin coroutines and Flow intentionally for async work and state propagation when the project already follows that model.
- Respect Material 3 and the existing design system before inventing custom interaction patterns.
- Hoist state thoughtfully and keep composables focused, testable, and free of unrelated orchestration logic.
- Manage recomposition intentionally. Avoid unnecessary state churn, unstable parameters, and work in composition that belongs elsewhere.
- Keep loading, error, and empty states explicit in the UI.
- Favor Hilt or the repository's existing dependency injection pattern instead of ad hoc wiring.
- Write ViewModel and use-case logic so it can be tested without the UI layer, and use Compose UI tests on critical user flows where practical.
